description:
Add C-linkage discovery to boost-config so a CLI can dlopen a plugin and enumerate its config schemas.

- factories_json<T>() -> std::string: jsonnet_factories<T>() serialized as a boost::json object {module-name: contents}. (Add near jsonnet.hpp.)
- BOOST_CONFIG_EXPORT(suffix, S): emits
    extern "C" __attribute__((visibility("default")))
    const char* boost_config_factories__##suffix() {
        static const std::string s = ::boost_config::factories_json<S>();
        return s.c_str();
    }
  NON-inline (real dlsym-able symbol); place in exactly ONE .cpp. Two-arg so a namespaced type gets a clean unqualified symbol suffix.
- Document the symbol prefix boost_config_factories__ as the enumeration convention (CLI scans .dynsym / nm -D for it, dlsym+call, parse the JSON, write .libjsonnet files).
- Tests: factories_json<MyStruct>() parses to an object containing mystruct+myparams; a test .cpp with BOOST_CONFIG_EXPORT compiled to a .so, then dlopen+dlsym the prefixed symbol and check the returned JSON. Keep PFR (no Describe).

design:
Emit Jsonnet source for a function that constructs an object matching schema T,
with docstrings as comments. Runtime function returning std::string.

API:
 - std::string jsonnet_factory<T>()            : the single file's contents for T
 - std::string jsonnet_default_invocation<S>(S const& = S{})
                                               : "MyParams(a=1, b=2, c=3)" used as
                                                 a nested-field default
 - std::map<std::string,std::string> jsonnet_factories<T>()
                                               : {module_name -> contents} for T and
                                                 EVERY nested struct type, deduped —
                                                 lets a caller write out a directory
                                                 of .libjsonnet files.

Emission algorithm for struct T (default-construct T to read defaults+docs via PFR):
  line 1: // <module_name(T)>.libjsonnet
  line 2: // @brief Construct a <type_name(T)> object
  per field (name via pfr::get_name<I,T>, doc via doc_of(field)):
          // @param <name> (<type_name of field's underlying type>) <doc>
  then, for each nested-STRUCT field (deduped): local <TypeName> = import "<module>.libjsonnet";
  then the function line:
          function (<name>=<default>, ...) { <name>: <name>, ... }
   where <default> is a Jsonnet literal of the field's default value:
     * scalar: int->"1", float/double->"2.0" (always a decimal point),
       bool->"true"/"false", string->quoted, vector->"[e, e, ...]"
     * nested struct: jsonnet_default_invocation<S>() -> "MyParams(a=1, b=2, c=3)"

Must reproduce EXACTLY (these are the acceptance goldens):

  // myparams.libjsonnet
  // @brief Construct a MyParams object
  // @param a (int) doc for a
  // @param b (int) doc for b
  // @param c (int) doc for c
  function (a=1, b=2, c=3) { a: a, b: b, c: c }

and

  // mystruct.libjsonnet
  // @brief Construct a MyStruct object
  // @param myparams (MyParams) doc for the whole myparams group
  local MyParams = import "myparams.libjsonnet";
  function (myparams=MyParams(a=1, b=2, c=3)) { myparams: myparams }

Notes / decisions to make while implementing:
 - undocumented field (plain type, no Documented): doc text is empty — decide
   "@param name (type)" with no trailing doc vs. omitting @param. Recommend
   keep the @param line (documents the parameter/type/default even without prose).
 - depends on type_name/module_name (ddm-6zj.3), Documented accessors (ddm-6zj.2).
 - the naming convention (lower-case) is the recursion key; jsonnet_factories
   walks nested struct fields to collect all modules.

Tests (test_jsonnet.cpp): byte-exact match of the two goldens above;
jsonnet_factories<MyStruct>() yields both "mystruct" and "myparams" entries;
float/bool/string/vector default formatting.

Refined design (evaluated against the user's proposed snippet). Two-specialization
Documented<T> plus traits that give a UNIFORM way to unwrap and to read the doc,
which the JSON and Jsonnet layers depend on.

Key evaluation points vs. the user's snippet:
 - Boost.PFR reflects the ENCLOSING config struct (MyConfig/MyStruct), never
   Documented itself. Documented having user-declared ctors (=> non-aggregate)
   is fine: an aggregate may contain non-aggregate members. PFR field-counting
   works because Documented<T> is constructible from a single argument (the doc
   defaults), so the loophole/ubiq machinery counts it as one field.
 - The aggregate specialization inherits from T so nested member access is
   transparent (cfg.myparams.a rather than cfg.myparams.value.a). But that makes
   the underlying-T access ASYMMETRIC (.value vs. base slice), so we MUST provide
   a uniform accessor `underlying()` on both, and both expose `.doc`.
 - Exclude arrays from the aggregate specialization (is_aggregate_v<int[3]> is
   true but you cannot inherit from an array). Note std::array is also an
   aggregate and would be inherited-from; acceptable, document it.
 - Keep operator T const&() and operator=(T) on the primary template only
   (scalar/vector sugar). Nested structs use member access, not these.

Proposed Documented.hpp:

  #pragma once
  #include <string_view>
  #include <type_traits>
  #include <utility>
  namespace boost_config {

  template <class> struct is_documented : std::false_type {};

  // primary: holds `.value` — scalars, std::vector<T>, any non-aggregate T
  template <class T, class Enable = void>
  struct Documented {
      using value_type = T;
      T value;
      std::string_view doc;
      constexpr Documented(T v, std::string_view d = {}) : value(std::move(v)), doc(d) {}
      constexpr operator T const&() const noexcept { return value; }
      constexpr Documented& operator=(T v) { value = std::move(v); return *this; }
      constexpr T const& underlying() const noexcept { return value; }
      constexpr T&       underlying()       noexcept { return value; }
  };

  // aggregate structs: inherit from T for transparent member access
  template <class T>
  struct Documented<T, std::enable_if_t<std::is_aggregate_v<T> && !std::is_array_v<T>>> : T {
      using value_type = T;
      std::string_view doc;
      constexpr Documented(T v, std::string_view d = {}) : T(std::move(v)), doc(d) {}
      constexpr T const& underlying() const noexcept { return static_cast<T const&>(*this); }
      constexpr T&       underlying()       noexcept { return static_cast<T&>(*this); }
  };

  template <class T, class E> struct is_documented<Documented<T,E>> : std::true_type {};
  template <class T> inline constexpr bool is_documented_v = is_documented<T>::value;

  // field_value_type_t<F>: underlying type of a struct field, unwrapping Documented
  template <class F> struct field_value_type { using type = F; };
  template <class T, class E> struct field_value_type<Documented<T,E>> { using type = T; };
  template <class F> using field_value_type_t = typename field_value_type<F>::type;

  // uniform field access used by json/jsonnet layers:
  //   auto const& v = as_value(field);        // Documented -> underlying(); else field
  //   std::string_view d = doc_of(field);     // Documented -> .doc; else {}
  // implement as two small overload sets / if-constexpr helpers.
  }

description:
New header-focused C++ package devel/boost-config/ giving Phlex node authors a way to describe a node's user-configuration schema as a plain C++ struct and:
 1) attach compile-time docstrings to fields via Documented<T>;
 2) (de)serialize the struct to/from the boost::json::value a node receives (value_from/value_to), with recursion over nested structs and std::vector<T>, and defined behavior on schema/JSON mismatch;
 3) emit Jsonnet factory functions (with docstrings as comments and one file per struct, lower-cased naming convention) via jsonnet_factory<T>().

Built with CMake in the same style as other devel/ packages (own git repo, cmake/<name>Config.cmake.in, CMakePresets.json). Depends only on Boost (external), so the devel/ superbuild auto-discovers it with no extra wiring. Environment confirmed: Boost 1.90 in extern/envs/gcc15/view — provides boost/pfr/core_name.hpp (compile-time field-name reflection, get_name<I,T>()/names_as_array), Boost.JSON, Boost.Core (demangle). C++20, gcc15.

See child issues for the ordered task breakdown and the refined design (evaluation of the user's proposed snippets against the goals).
